</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0110-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0110-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See particularly <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0097&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-04-02-0097-fn-0001#GEWN-02-04-02-0097-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 29 May 1757, n.1</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0115" class="document">10 June 1757</a>, for references to these parties of Cherokee.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0110-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0110-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>An account of the charges for supplying the Indians on their march to the Carolina border, 924 June, signed by Sgt. John David Wilper, is in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0110-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0110-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Peter Hogs company was at Vauses fort in Augusta County.</p>

</div>
